Here's a comparison of `write`, `puts`, and `printf` in C:

## **write()** (System Call)
```c
#include <unistd.h>
ssize_t write(int fd, const void *buf, size_t count);
```
- **Low-level system call** - direct interface to the OS
- **Unbuffered** - writes immediately to file descriptor
- **Binary-safe** - can handle null bytes (`\0`)
- **Returns bytes written** or -1 on error
- **No formatting** - just raw bytes
- **Requires file descriptor** (1 for stdout)

```c
write(1, "Hello\n", 6);  // Write to stdout
```

## **puts()** (Standard Library)
```c
#include <stdio.h>
int puts(const char *s);
```
- **Buffered** - uses stdio buffer
- **Automatically adds newline** - appends `\n`
- **Not binary-safe** - stops at null terminator
- **Simpler** - just outputs string
- **Returns non-negative** on success, EOF on error

```c
puts("Hello");  // Outputs "Hello\n"
```

## **printf()** (Standard Library)
```c
#include <stdio.h>
int printf(const char *format, ...);
```
- **Buffered** - uses stdio buffer
- **Formatted output** - supports placeholders (`%d`, `%s`, etc.)
- **No automatic newline** (unless you add `\n`)
- **Variable arguments** - can take multiple parameters
- **Returns characters printed** or negative on error

```c
printf("Hello %s!\n", "world");  // Outputs "Hello world!\n"
```

## Key Differences

| Feature | write() | puts() | printf() |
|---------|---------|---------|----------|
| **Level** | System call | Library function | Library function |
| **Buffering** | Unbuffered | Buffered | Buffered |
| **Formatting** | No | No | Yes |
| **Newline** | Manual | Automatic | Manual |
| **Binary-safe** | Yes | No | No |
| **Speed** | Slower (syscall) | Faster | Slower (parsing) |
| **Error return** | Bytes written | Non-negative/EOF | Chars printed/negative |

## When to Use Each

- **write()**: 
  - When you need raw performance for large data
  - Binary data (images, network packets)
  - Direct control over file descriptors
  - Real-time logging (no buffering delay)

- **puts()**:
  - Simple string output with newline
  - When you don't need formatting
  - Cleaner code for fixed strings

- **printf()**:
  - Formatted output with variables
  - Complex string construction
  - Most general-purpose output needs

## Example Comparison
```c
// All output "Hello\n" in different ways

// Using write
write(1, "Hello\n", 6);

// Using puts
puts("Hello");

// Using printf
printf("Hello\n");
printf("%s\n", "Hello");
```

## Performance Note
For simple string output, `puts("text")` is generally faster than `printf("text\n")` because `printf` has to parse the format string even when there are no format specifiers.
